t></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uworthyiam.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Worthy Iam</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cyber Pimp</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/2/01 9:00:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> I am now on the list of people who need Ragefire.<br>
<br>
Pretty much all the clerics I know are honorable, but, just to keep us covered, let us discuss some ideas for rules on people who need it.<br>
<br>
My suggestion is, first come/first serve. If you are the first cleric at the camp, awaiting the spawn, then, you get first shot at it when it POPS. If the person leaves the camp, then, the next person in line gets the lead spot. Now, most of us have enough people in their debts that we could form an attack force pretty fast. What would be a reasonable time to give some one to call troops in before letting the next person call their people in? 15? 30 min?<br>
<br>
Also, and, this is just my opinion, I am looking for feedback, I think that it should be the cleric him/herself that waits. (is this practical? I have not done it yet, so do not know.) Should the person be allowed to have a guildmate hold the spot for him/her? i.e. A monk with FD?<br>
<br>
I am posting this, looking for suggestions. Ragefire is our bottleneck, and, if we discuss things civil now, it may prevent problems in the future.<br>
<br>
Thanks for listening! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <p>-Worthy Iam: Templar of the 55th Circle. Officer and founding memeber of The Chosen Counsel. (Piñata of Many a Mob.)
</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uworthyiam.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Worthy Iam</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0> at: 6/2/01 10:05:25 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/usalamren.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Salamren</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/3/01 1:14:53 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1>  The Luclin server has a very nice ragefire system. Unfortunately with a lot of the &quot;might makes right&quot; attitude here It seems like a bit of a long shot to get something like that started here on Lanys. <br>
<br>
Salamren Mechamender<br>
Gnomish Templar <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uerikia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Erikia</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/3/01 4:31:41 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> Ragefire is a 1-96 hour spawn, I thinks it is completely unreasonalbe to expect a cleric to sit there, the entire time, till he spawns using some list method. It is inherently unfair to the more casual player. I think it need to be whoever get there first, with makings of a raid, gets to take a crack at him. To me the making of a raid is a group or two there in zone. Ragefire is not that difficult a mob. I think there should be a reasonable time limit to &quot;get started&quot;. Maybe an hour or 2. After that it should pass to the next person who was in zone with the same &quot;raid making&quot;. <br>
<br>
Erikia <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uworthyiam.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Worthy Iam</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Cyber Pimp</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/3/01 6:10:26 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> Hmmm. The reason I do not totally agree with that is because that promotes Might Makes Right. I am pretty lucky, I have alot of friends, and, I could probably pull togeather alot of people fairly fast. But, what of that cleric who was there 4 hours before me? They put in the dedication to camp and wait. If they had Logged, it would default to my turn, but, they stayed. If I got a group of people there before they could, without giving them at least a fair shot at rallying their forces, then, that, in my humble opinion, would not be much better than Kill stealing. That is why I am getting input, to see what every one would agree on as fair. Killing Rage Faster will not make it Respawn any faster, so, time can be taken to get togeather forces, as long as it is reasonable. Giving some one 20-30 minutes to get their raiding party set would not be too bad, and, you can call your own forces too if you think they will not have the Man(Woman) Power to do it. How would you feel if you were a cleric in a smaller guild, that did not have some of the resources that the more Ubar Guilds did? You showed your dedication, camped the spawn and held your spot for I do not know how many hours, and, some one else, who had more firepower available came in 10 minutes after he spawned, and just took him, cuz you did not have the same network? I am just looking for a way to make it fair for all. The Casual player, as you say, would not be showing the dedication to camp the spawn, and, if he did, then, he should have a chance to get it.<br>
<br>
When Celina went for Ragefire, she accidently gave her Pearl to some ones Pet. Elmedico was in the background, ready to do his epic too. BUT, he did not rush it. When it was realized that a mistake was made, him, and his group waited patiently, to give Celina time to resolve the mistake. They waited probably at least a half hour or so, till we came to the conclusion that, at that point in time, there was nothing we could do. At that point, Elmedico took his turn, and, I assume got what he needed. The point is, he acted with Honor.(/cheer Elmedico)  Sure, he could have just pushed in when she accidently gave the shimmering pearl to the pet. He did not tho, and still got what he wanted. If he had gone about it diffrerent, the loss of a good reputation would have soured the whole epic experience.<br>
<br>
Please continue with your input. Thanks! <p>-Worthy Iam: Templar of the 55th Circle. Officer and founding memeber of The Chosen Counsel. (Piñata of Many a Mob.)
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ugtath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gtath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/01 12:06:25 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.blizzard.com/images/broodwar/popup/corsair.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Killing Rage Faster will not make it Respawn any faster<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes it will.  When Ragefire dies, the respawn timer is reset.  You can have several Ragefire killings between Nagafens, so it benefits everyone to kill him as quickly as possible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I am just looking for a way to make it fair for all.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Your goal is noble, but all you're going to do here is get some agreement from some people, and others will completely ignore your agreement, causing bad feelings on both sides, and probably more spam of the shitlist.<br>
<br>
You pointed out that there was sufficient restraint and nobility displayed in the case of Celina and Elmedico, and that's probably what you're going to have to hope for when it's your turn.<br>
<br>
The answer to your question unfortunately is that might does indeed make right under the rules that Verant has given us.  The way that might is exercised is completely up to the individual who holds the shimmering pearl. <p><img src="http://nomaru.homestead.com/files/SigPigs/Gtathsig.jpg">
<br>
High Priest of Conquest<br>
<a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=42740" target="_blank">My profile at Castersrealm</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ufelishannasecretlight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Felishanna Secretlight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/01 6:11:01 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> OOC.<br>
I am at the same stage now. But to be honest, I'm only at this stage after two months needing the Chardok note because my good and very selfless friend Ellyria gave me a note she had looted via multiquesting to get the pearl. Motivation to complete this quest has really been lacking for me. No loot item is worth making one feel awful, and I feel, that is how things might end up.<br>
<br>
You see, I like Erikia's idea, mostly because it shows common decency to others. Worthy's plan too seems reasonable. But look at Gtath's statement, made without malice, I know, that Verant makes Might Right. Well, no, it doesn't make it *right*, it just makes it *legal*. Players make decisions on how they act, not Verant, Verant just takes no responsibility. In some ways, I cannot blame them, it keeps them out of lots of messy issues that they don't want to get into.<br>
<br>
The idea that I might spend 10 hours camping a spawn, only to have it pop and me need 30 mins or more to gather friends and others to help me kill it, because I am in a guild of 4 or 5 high level players, and worse because this is a roleplayed character who may not ask 25% of characters due to her own alignment grouping restrictions (and their friends who won't come if the former can't), only to have some (in my view) rude and greedy person bring their guild in because they arrived 10 mins before he popped and saw it, and having far faster mobilization than I can ever match, just sickens me. I know most players are not ever that rude, but some are, and thats a fact. So ultimately, though I do not agree with Gtath's statement that Verant makes Might Right, I do know the thrust of his point is &gt; some will ignore any decent agreement made by others, JUST BECAUSE THEY CAN.<br>
<br>
Time will tell. Good luck Worthy and Erikia, if I do start this camp sometime soon, if I arrive to find you camping it first, sitting in the Lair of the Dragon, I'll either leave wishing you good luck, or join to aid your quest. I'd certainly come to help either of you kill him for your epics, if you asked it.<br>
<br>
Some day Verant might I mean just might make an insta-spawn varient of this dragon, perhaps harder to kill, and that will give those of us every bit as dedicated and skilled as the big guild powergamers but who play a different style a decent shot at this, without having to face the less honourable and more greedy elements of the community whom we tend to otherwise avoid in our gaming.<br>
<br>
Take care.<br>
 <p>------------------------------<BR>
Felishanna Secretlight<BR>
High Priestess of Tunare<BR>
Heroes of the Old Lands<BR>
Lanys T'Vyl.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ueqaquinas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EQAquinas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t d00d!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/01 12:06:28 pm)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> I think Erikia raises a valid issue about the interests of more casual players.  The idea of might makes right is generally unpopular, but I also dont care for a system of massive free time makes right.  At any given time, there are likely to be multiple clerics wanting to kill Ragefire, and it is also likely that some of them will have the ability to camp the spawn for long periods of time (theyre students off for the summer, theyre kids, they dont work outside the home, etc.)  Others of us may only be able to camp a few hours here and there.  Im not inclined to participate in a system that does not give the casual player a reasonable shot at a Ragefire spawn.<br>
<br>
Heres a thought: what if there were a cap on the amount of time you were entitled to camp before letting someone else have a shot?  You could show up and youd have, say, two hours to wait for the spawn.  If no one else is around after two hours, you can wait as long as you like.  But if another cleric shows up after your two hours (or whatever the period is), then he gets a shift, and so on.  That way the spawn chances would be spread out among the various people wanting to kill Ragefire, rather than given entirely to the person who can log on the earliest and stay on the latest.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Should the person be allowed to have a guildmate hold the spot for him/her? i.e. A monk with FD?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I definitely dont think this should be permitted.  If someone wants to walk an FDer into the lair and let the computer run for hours, thats fine, but I dont see how that should create any special priority for killing Zordak.<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ugtath.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gtath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/01 1:49:35 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.blizzard.com/images/broodwar/popup/corsair.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> Maybe I sound cold or callous, but it seems like some people think they are &quot;entitled&quot; to their epic weapon, and that entitlement allows them to make rules that everyone else is then forced to follow.  The truth is that the reward will go to the individual who is the most efficient at executing the required tasks.  If you don't think you can &quot;beat out the other guy&quot;, then either you will be waiting in line for a long time, or you need to learn how to marshal your forces more efficiently. <br>
<br>
If you are faster or more efficient than someone who is &quot;in front of you&quot;, you have every right within the rules of the game to blaze ahead and do your thing.  It is up to you at that moment to decide if you will stand down and give someone else their chance before you.<br>
<br>
My friends, trying to make rules in this thread is an exercise in futility, because there will always be some other cleric who doesn't agree to be bound to these &quot;rules&quot; that you all agree to here, and prefers to follow the rules to which we are all bound as a function of playing the game. <p><img src="http://nomaru.homestead.com/files/SigPigs/Gtathsig.jpg">
<br>
High Priest of Conquest<br>
<a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=42740" target="_blank">My profile at Castersrealm</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ufelishannasecretlight.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Felishanna Secretlight</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/4/01 5:47:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire: Lets make some rules.</span><hr size=1> OOC.<br>
Gtath, no-one is entitled to their epic weapon (or any item), of course not, and no-one said they were, nor implied it.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately you are 100% right, not all have any sense of honour and self-respect. Some are motivated by pure greed and/or enjoy the feeling of power/bullying others. So ok, in EQ it is LEGAL to do as you describe with no regard, but it does not make it reasonable or convey any respect with others. Indeed, the only people who respect it are the others who advocate it because they are both greedy and feel they can benefit by it.<br>
<br>
Your summary is sadly probably true. It is *probably* an excercise in futility. But good on Worthy et al for trying anyway. And those who just use force to override another will likely be publically lambasted for the greedy self-important individual that they are (not that that type will care, mind).<br>
<br>
Sigh. Guess that was a rant.<br>
<br>
