<br>
First off: I am not a Cleric - I hope this means that my views will be un-biased. I will propose the guidelines so that everyone else may then begin to argue over it. <br>
<br>
1) That Ragefire be treated like a camp with the camper having the right to kill. But only Clerics should have the right to camp him - ie: no monks or rogues can claim the camp... heck no other class save the cleric. <br>
<br>
2) Once the mob pops - said Cleric will be given 30 minutes to assemble forces, (that's 30 minutes from pop) if the attack is not started in 30 minutes, whoever has the next ready and waiting attack force should then ask for the right to attack. The original camper should then give permission for the second in line to attack. Note: In the event that there are SEVERAL secondary forces in waiting - the right goes to the MOST POWERFUL force assembled... basically - once Rage pops - it's a race to see who can assemble the largest strikeforce... to calculate the requirements for largest strikeforce - Take all assembled players in the force - deduct 35(an arbritary number I plucked from thin air) from their levels then add the totals - highest value wins. <br>
<br>
3) If the original camper is mere minutes away from beggining his assault the original camper may ask for 5 minutes grace. At the end of those 5 minutes - he either lands a blow and plays the price or seceeds the assault to the secondary camper. The Secondary camper (the largest force present) must immediately begin the attack. Only a few minutes - say 5 will be allowed for buff stage - after which the attack must begin. Or it goes to the next largest force. Which may be the forces of the original camper.<br>
<br>
Conduct before pop:<br>
<br>
4) In the event a Cleric comes to camp the mob and finds another Cleric sitting there (thus claiming the camp) the newly arrived cleric may ask the currently camping cleric to state the list of camping clerics and ask to have his name added.<br>
<br>
5) The currently camping cleric must list everyone on the list in proper order... and THEN check to make sure that everyone on the list is still online... anyone who cannot be contacted should be stricken from the list, to allow for LDs or zoners plyers should be given 5 minutes before the name is stricken from the list.<br>
<br>
6) Both the camping cleric and the newly arrived cleric will make note of the list - every cleric must contact every other cleric on the list so everyone knows who is next.<br>
<br>
7) When the camping cleric has had enough - he then calls the next on list to take his spot - he must also inform EVERY other cleric on the list about who is taking over. If the next on list is unable to take over -then go down the list.<br>
<br>
Edit: number 8 was taken out becuase it was a stupid rule to have in place. To read it - check Rugen's post.<br>
<br>
Hypothetical situations and the rules in action:<br>
<br>
eg: FirstAid comes to the camp and finds no one there... FirstAid then begins the camp, a short while later SecondHeaven shows up... SecondHeaven asks FirstAid for list, FirstAid tells SecondHeaven he is next on list. SecondHeaven may now do as he wishes, though he probaly should keep FirstAid company. But lets say Second Heaven wanders off. ThirdLife shows up for camp, finds FirstAid there and asks for list.<br>
<br>
The list looks like this:<br>
FirstAid<br>
SecondHeaven<br>
<br>
FirstAid tells ThirdLife, he is second on list after SecondHeaven. Both FirstAid and ThirdLife contact SecondHeaven to make sure he is on-line.<br>
<br>
SecondHeaven must reply ASAP. Both FirstAid and ThirdLife should keep trying to contact SecondHeaven. After 5 minutes... with no response from SecondHeaven, then SecondHeaven is stricken from the List.<br>
<br>
The list now looks like this:<br>
FirstAid<br>
ThirdLife<br>
<br>
Lets say SecondHeaven returns to camp one hour later and finds FirstAid still there. SecondHeaven asks to take the camp. FirstAid will tell him that he is now SECOND on list after ThirdLife (but first they must make sure ThirdLife is still online). Let's say Third Life is still on line.<br>
<br>
The list now looks like this:<br>
FirstAid<br>
ThirdLife<br>
SecondHeaven<br>
<br>
20 hours later First Aid gives up and hands the camp to ThirdLife. FirstAid must now inform everyone on list that he is leaving camp so that everyone may alter the list accordingly. Update the list for those who have gone missing or no show accordingly... those giving up the camp should inform everyone else 10 minutes before they have to go so that the 5 minutes seek time can be fully used. ThirdLife then takes the camp. I would suggest that everyone on the list head to the camp though... well all those close to being next in line. <br>
<br>
The reason is this:<br>
<br>
So that they can inform everyone else of the list - preferably the camping cleric should wait till the next in line is there...<br>
<br>
Let's say that ThirdLife is now owner of the camp - but is taking his time getting there. During this time... SecondHeaven is at the camp and Ragefire pops. SecondHeaven must now inform everyone on list that Ragefire has popped and so the 30 minute timer has started. ThirdLife now has 30 minutes from the time SecondHeaven informs everyone of the pop to attack Ragefire. If ThirdLife arrives within 30 minutes and is almost ready - he may have the 5 minutes grace to land the blow.... failing that the LARGEST strike force available now has 5 minutes to land the blow.<br>
<br>
Let's say that after 30 minutes - ThirdLife is not yet in zone - he's in EC and desperately runnig to the camp. At this point I'd like to ask whoever has their strikeforce in place to be lenient BUT - to prevent people from taking a lackadasical attitude - they now have the RIGHT to attack Ragefire ... this is 30 minutes after pop - and the camping cleric not being present. Note that is is the CAMPING CLERIC ON THE LIST that MUST be present. If his strikeforce is present but not HIM/HER then the right to attack goes to the next force. Moral: do not delay in getting to the camp.<br>
<br>
<br>
Hopefully those hypothetical situations helped clear things up.<br>
<br>
<br>
FINALLY: the 0th rule<br>
<br>
As has been pointed out - guilds/groups who are powerful enough need not pay any attention to the *proposed* rules of conduct. But if a sizable portion of you clerics out there rattify this proposal then the party that decides to dis-regard these rules of conduct will do so at the risk of upsetting the rest of the Cleric community. <br>
<br>
It ain't prettey - but it's better than FFA.<br>
<br>
